princeton_ansible.title: [lib-statistics] Updating private key that will expire next month
Deduplicate role inclusion for molecule testing?

comments.body:
I don't think Ansible deduplicates down the nested tree, and we have a lot of nested dependencies. For example, the dependency tree for the `lib_jobs` role looks like this:

- ruby (which depends on common)
- deploy_user (which also depends on common)
- mariadb (which depends on deploy_user ((which in turn depends on common)) )
- redis (no dependencies!!!)
- sidekiq_worker (which depends on rails_app ((which in turn depends on common, bind9, deploy_user, passenger, postgresql, nodejs. . . most of which have dependencies of their own)) )
- rails_app (which depends on common, bind9, deploy_user, passenger, postgresql, nodejs . . . see above)
- hr_share (which depends on samba)
This makes me think we should move away from using meta for dependencies and toward just putting everything in playbooks.

That's a good idea, and would help with visibility. We can do this one role at a time. 

Steps to implement:

- [ ] update playbooks in `playbooks/` to run all role dependencies currently defined in `roles/<role_name>/meta/main.yml` files
- [ ] remove `meta/main.yml` files from roles
- [ ] configure molecule to use the production playbooks instead of duplicating playbooks in `roles/<role_name>/molecule/default/` (to prevent drift in testing)

Anything else?
See also [this SO post](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58411630/molecule-tests-for-ansible-roles-how-to-structure-to-avoid-duplication).
@carolyncole I'd interested if you have thoughts here, since you and @kayiwa  worked so much on the molecule setup.
Okay, I tried a  quick "proof of concept" (#2693), which showed me how complex this change would be. Definitely something to discuss broadly.
